SWoOz is a program of research developed at INSERM U846, Bron (France) by Guillaume Gibert. It is based on a state-of-the art integrated hardware/software robotic system. Through teleoperation and teleperception, a person is directly linked with a humanoid robot. He/She lives remotely as if he/she was in the robot’s body moving in real-time like the person. In addition, this person (i.e., the teleoperator) perceives the scene as if he/she was the robot. The teleoperator puts him/herself in the robot’s shoes. This platform gives access to “bottom-up” signals coming from the robot’s sensors (vision, audition, haptic) and “top-down” signals coming from the human’s behaviors translated into robot’s encoders. Thanks to this platform, we study Human-Robot Interaction (HRI) by applying online manipulation of one specific behavior (e.g., eye vergence) at a time and preserving the rest of the behaviors intact. In addition, we study body transfer illusions by applying mismatch in multisensory (video and tactile) inputs through teleperception.
